### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

Consider the following `compatForm`

```ts
form = compatForm(
    signal({ firstName: '', lastName: new FormControl('') }),
    (path) => {
      disabled(path, () => this.form().submitting());
    },
  );
```

which should be conditionally disabled when the form is submitting.

In the current example, only the regular `firstName` path that does not use an reactive control will be disabled. On the other compat path, the `disabled` metadata is propagates down but is not synced with the reactive control. Further, trying to use `disabled` specifically, with the compat path

```ts
disabled(path.lastName, () => this.form().submitting());
```
indicates that this declarative rule is not meant to be used on such a path:

```
Argument of type 'SchemaPathTree<FormControl<string | null>, Child>' is not assignable to parameter of type 'SchemaPath<unknown, 1, Root>'.
  The types of '[ÉµÉµTYPE].supportsRules' are incompatible between these types.
    Type '2' is not assignable to type '1'.
```

### Proposed solution

Consider increasing the compatibility between signal and reactive forms by adding `disabled` to the supported rules for compat paths  so that the `disabled` state can be declaratively defined. 

This would require establishing a state sync between the signal and reactive form. This sync could optionally include back-propagation of the disabled state if it would be changed imperatively on the reactive control.

### Alternatives considered

One can manually implement specific disabled logic via an effect:
```ts
effect(() => {
    const submitting = this.form().submitting();

    untracked(() => {
      if (submitting) {
        this.form.lastName().control().disable();
      } else {
        this.form.lastName().control().enable();
      }
    });
```

or even sync the disabled meta data with the control to enable root updates:

```ts
effect(() => {
    const disabled = this.form.lastName().disabled();

    untracked(() => {
      if (disabled) {
        this.form.lastName().control().disable();
      } else {
        this.form.lastName().control().enable();
      }
    });
  });
```

